span%3E%20(%20Russian%20newspaper)%20President%20Zelensky%20requested%20a%20face-to-face%20meeting%20with%20Putin.%20Lavrov%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Fworld%2Feurope%2Fputin-zelenskiy-meeting-needed-once-sides-closer-key-issues-russias-lavrov-2022-03-28%2F%5C%22%3Erejected%3C%2Fa%3E%20this%20and%20said%2C%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%20%E2%80%9C%20It%20should%20happen%20once%20the%20two%20sides%20are%20closer%20to%20agreeing%20on%20key%20issues%E2%80%9D.%20This%20rebuff%20brought%20a%20temporary%20halt%20to%20the%20sequence%20of%20negotiations.%20It%20also%20coincided%20with%20the%20start%20of%20a%20Ukrainian%20counter-offensive%20on%20March%2022%2C%20which%2C%20by%20April%203%2C%20had%20ended%20Russian%20threat%20to%20Kyiv.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0The%20seventh%20round%20of%20talks%20on%20March%2029%20saw%20the%20renewal%20of%20face-to-face%20negotiations%20in%20Istanbul.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.eurointegration.com.ua%2Feng%2Farticles%2F2022%2F03%2F30%2F7136915%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EEuropean%20Pravda%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3Ereported%20that%20this%20had%20so%20far%20been%20the%20%E2%80%98most%20effective%20round%20of%20Ukraine-Russian%20negotiations%E2%80%99.%20The%20discussion%20centred%20on%20a%20draft%20treaty%2C%20the%20gist%20of%20which%20was%20permanent%20Ukrainian%20neutrality%20and%20non-nuclear%20status%2C%20in%20return%20for%20which%20Ukraine%20would%20have%20security%20guarantees%20similar%20to%20Article%205%20of%20the%20NATO%20military%20alliance%20from%20China%2C%20Russia%2C%20UK%2C%20France%2C%20Belarus%20and%20others.%20Ukraine%20would%20also%20start%20a%2015-year%20consultation%20period%20on%20the%20status%20of%20Crimea%2C%20though%20reserving%20the%20right%20to%20reconquer%20Luhansk%20and%20Donetsk%20(Ukrainian%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pravda.com.ua%2Feng%2Fnews%2F2023%2F06%2F14%2F7406819%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EPravda%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E).%20For%20its%20part%2C%20Russia%20would%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fnational-security%2F2022%2F03%2F29%2Fukraine-russia-turkey-negotiations%2F%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9Cdrastically%20reduce%E2%80%9D%20military%20activity%3C%2Fa%3E%20near%20Kyiv%20to%20%E2%80%98create%20the%20necessary%20conditions%20for%20further%20negotiations%E2%80%9D.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3EUkraine%E2%80%99s%20successful%20counter-offensive%20had%20started%20a%20week%20before%20the%20Istanbul%20peace%20talks.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%20The%20Russian%20offer%20to%20%E2%80%98withdraw%E2%80%99%20on%20March%2029%20was%20thus%20far%20from%20voluntary.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThis%20draft%20was%20the%20one%20Putin%20waved%20on%20television%20on%20June%2017%2C%202023.%20He%20called%20it%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftass.ru%2Fpolitika%2F17997587%5C%22%3E%E2%80%9Cnot%20bad%20result%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20talks%20of%20March%2029%20ended%20in%20the%20expectation%20that%20the%20draft%20agreement%20would%20be%20initialled%20by%3C%2Fspan%3E%20%3Cspan%3Ethe%20principals%2C%20laying%20the%20foundations%20for%20a%20compromise%20peace.%20Putin%20even%20suggested%20meeting%20Zelensky.%3C%2Fspan%3E%20%3Cspan%3EThis%20never%20happened%2C%20and%20that%20was%20the%20end%20of%20the%20bilateral%20talks.%20Russian%20foreign%20minister%20Sergey%20Lavrov%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Fworld%2Feurope%2Frussia-says-talks-with-ukraine-are-not-going-in-any-form-ifax-2022-05-17%2F%5C%22%3Estated%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20%E2%80%9C%20Washington%2C%20London%20and%20Brussels%20want%20to%20use%20Ukraine%20to%20their%20advantage%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9Cno%20peace%20deal%20can%20be%20made%E2%80%9D.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3EZelensky%20stated%20that%20Ukraine%20would%20not%20agree%20to%20peace%20until%20Russia%20agreed%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usatoday.com%2Fstory%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2F2022%2F05%2F25%2Fukraine-russia-invasion-live-updates%2F9916925002%2F%5C%22%3Ereturn%20Crimea%20and%20Donbas%20region%20to%20Ukraine%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ETo%20sum%20up%3A%20in%20the%20early%20weeks%20that%20followed%20the%20Russian%20invasion%20of%20Ukraine%2C%20the%20two%20engaged%20in%20substantial%20attempts%20to%20negotiate%20a%20peace%20settlement.%20These%20could%20have%20ended%20the%20war%20before%20the%20devastation%20of%20Ukraine%E2%80%99s%20infrastructure%2C%20the%20massive%20loss%20of%20lives%2C%20and%20the%20increased%20risk%20of%20unchecked%20escalation.%20They%20featured%20an%20offer%20by%20Ukraine%20not%20to%20join%20NATO%20in%20return%20for%20equivalent%20security%20guarantees.%20Crucial%20points%20of%20disagreement%20about%20Crimea%20and%20Donbas%2C%20as%20well%20as%20about%20the%20practicability%20of%20the%20non-Nato%20guarantees%2C%20remained.%20But%20on%20March%2029%2C%20both%20sides%20apparently%20expected%20to%20go%20on%20talking.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EReasons%20for%20Failure%C2%A0%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EWas%20there%20a%20real%20chance%20for%20peace%20in%20March%202022%3F%20If%20so%2C%20why%20was%20it%20lost%3F%20Let%E2%80%99s%20take%20these%20questions%20in%20turn.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20two%20sides%20were%20never%20as%20close%20to%20each%20other%20as%20the%20formulae%20they%20concocted%20suggested.%20Yes%2C%20Ukraine%20was%20willing%20to%20renounce%20joining%20NATO%2C%20but%20knew%20that%20equivalent%20security%20guarantees%20by%20the%20great%20powers%20would%20be%20hard%20to%20come%20by.%20Nor%20was%20there%20any%20real%20prospect%20of%20Russia%20%E2%80%98negotiating%20away%E2%80%99%20its%20annexation%20of%20Crimea%20in%202014.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAnd%20as%20far%20as%20known%2C%20no%20progress%20had%20been%20made%20in%20settling%20the%20future%20of%20the%20Donbas-the%20Russian-speaking%20provinces%20of%20eastern%20and%20south-eastern%20Ukraine.%20Agreements%20between%20Russia%20and%20Ukraine%2C%20brokered%20by%20France%20and%20Germany%2C%20known%20as%20Minsk%20I%20and%20Minsk%20II%20intended%20to%20give%20the%20provinces%20a%20degree%20of%20autonomy%20within%20Ukraine%20had%20collapsed%20in%202015.%20Now%20they%20were%20partly%20occupied%20by%20Russian%20troops.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EImportant%20in%20determining%20the%20immediate%20outcome%20were%20the%20fortunes%20of%20war.%20It%20was%20their%20initial%20failure%20to%20capture%20Kyiv%20which%20got%20the%20Russians%20talking%3B%20their%20continuing%20offensive%20in%20March%20which%20brought%20Ukraine%20to%20the%20table.%20With%20the%20success%20of%20the%20Ukrainian%20counter-offensive%20of%20March%2022%2C%20the%20Russians%20had%20a%20renewed%20incentive%20to%20negotiate%2C%20while%20Ukraine%20was%20starting%20to%20scent%20victory.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20Ukrainian%20counter-attack%20also%20crucially%20strengthened%20the%20western%20resolve%20to%20support%20Ukraine%2C%20leading%20to%20the%20withdrawal%20by%20Ukraine%20of%20even%20cosmetic%20concessions.%20As%20the%20Ukrainian%20army%20continued%20to%20inflict%20defeats%20on%20the%20Russians%2C%20and%20western%20military%20aid%20was%20ramped%20up%20in%20the%20summer%202022%2C%20Ukraine%20had%20little%20further%20reason%20to%20talk%20to%20the%20Russians.%20The%20damage%20inflicted%20by%20continued%20fighting%20would%20be%20paid%20back%20by%20victory.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThese%20were%20the%20structural%20obstacles%20to%20successful%20peace%20negotiations.%20However%2C%20there%20were%20also%20two%20dramatic%20events%20which%20tilted%20the%20balance%20against%20peace.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAs%20Russian%20forces%20were%20driven%20out%20of%20the%20Kyiv%20region%20at%20the%20end%20of%20March%2C%20Ukrainians%20claimed%20to%20have%20discovered%20evidence%20of%20atrocities%20%E2%80%93%20rapes%2C%20murders%2C%20massacres%2C%20looting%2C%20indiscriminate%20bombings%20and%20other%20war%20crimes%20%E2%80%93%20in%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pravda.com.ua%2Farticles%2F2022%2F05%2F5%2F7344096%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EBucha%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%2C%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Flife.pravda.com.ua%2Fsociety%2F2022%2F04%2F6%2F248117%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EIrpin%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%2C%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pravda.com.ua%2Farticles%2F2022%2F04%2F9%2F7338269%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EBorodianka%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%2C%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pravda.com.ua%2Feng%2Fnews%2F2022%2F05%2F4%2F7343968%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EAzovstal%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E.%20These%20atrocious%20events%2C%20Russian%20responsibility%20for%20which%20has%20been%20confirmed%20by%20the%20UN%20High%20Commission%20on%20Human%20Rights%2C%20gave%20Ukraine%20an%20additional%20reason%20to%20break%20off%20negotiations%2C%20one%20strongly%20supported%20by%20the%20West.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAn%20even%20bigger%20obstacle%20to%20further%20talks%20may%20have%20been%20the%20arrival%20in%20Kyiv%2C%20on%20April%206%2C%20of%20British%20Prime%20Minister%20Boris%20Johnson%20%E2%80%9CJohnson%20brought%20two%20simple%20messages%20to%20Kyiv.%20The%20first%20is%20that%20Putin%20is%20a%20war%20criminal%3B%20he%20should%20be%20pressured%2C%20not%20negotiated%20with.%20And%20the%20second%20is%20that%20even%20if%20Ukraine%20is%20ready%20to%20sign%20some%20agreements%20on%20guarantees%20with%20Putin%2C%20they%20%5Bthe%20NATO%20powers%5D%20are%20not%E2%80%9D.%20is%20how%20one%20of%20Zelenskyy%E2%80%99s%20negotiators%20associates%2C%20Savyd%20Arakmahia%2C%20summed%20up%20the%20gist%20of%20Johnson%E2%80%99s%20remarks.%20Three%20days%20after%20Johnson%20returned%20home%20Putin%20announced%20publicly%20that%20talks%20with%20Ukraine%20%E2%80%9Chad%20reached%20a%20dead%20end%E2%80%9D.%20For%20his%20part%20Johnson%20promised%20Zelensky%20%24130m%20of%20military%20equipment%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2022%2F04%2F09%2Fworld%2Feurope%2Fboris-johnson-kyiv-ukraine-aid.html%5C%22%3E%24500m%20in%20in%20financial%20aid%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%2C%20while%20President%20Biden%20announced%20a%20%24%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.defense.gov%2FNews%2FNews-Stories%2FArticle%2FArticle%2F3006622%2Fpresident-biden-announces-new-800m-in-military-assistance-to-ukraine%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3E800m%20military%20package%20to%20Ukraine%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EJohnson%E2%80%99s%20intervention%20has%20been%20discounted%20on%20the%20ground%20that%20he%20was%20in%20no%20position%20to%20tell%20the%20Ukrainian%20government%20what%20to%20do.%20This%20is%20legally%20correct%2C%20but%20vacuous.%20He%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3Ewas%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%20in%20a%20position%20to%20tell%20them%20whether%20NATO%20powers%20would%20be%20willing%20to%20join%20Russia%20in%20guaranteeing%20Ukrainian%20independence%20outside%20NATO%2C%20and%20under%20what%20conditions%20Britain%20(and%20the%20USA)%20would%20supply%20further%20military%20and%20economic%20aid.%20Had%20Johnson%E2%80%99s%20promise%20of%20support%20been%20conditional%20rather%20than%20unconditional%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fopinions%2F2022%2F09%2F22%2Fputin-ukraine-threats-biden-cuban-missile-crisis%2F%5C%22%3Eit%20is%20inconceivable%20that%20negotiations%20would%20not%20have%20continued.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EWhat%20of%20the%20future%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EWith%20the%20military%20situation%20in%20Ukraine%20now%20in%20stalemate%2C%20there%20is%20predictable%20new%20pressure%20for%20peace%20talks.%20There%20have%20been%20reports%20of%20%E2%80%98secret%20talks%E2%80%99%20between%20US%20and%20Russian%20officials.%20There%20have%20been%20public%20peace%20initiatives%20by%20China%2C%20the%20Vatican%2C%20Brazil%2C%20Mexico%20and%20others.%20Thought%20leaders%20like%20Anatol%20Lieven%20and%20Jeffrey%20Sachs%20have%20strongly%20argued%20for%20an%20immediate%20ceasefire.%20These%20initiatives%20seem%20to%20be%20based%20on%20a%20sense%20that%20the%20war%20is%20going%20nowhere%2C%20but%20that%20were%20it%20to%20go%20somewhere%2C%20it%20could%20easily%20escalate%20into%20a%20nuclear%20confrontation.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EWhen%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20foreign%20minister%20Sergei%20Lavrov%20said%20that%20the%20Ukraine%20conflict%20%E2%80%98is%20not%20as%20much%20about%20Ukraine%20as%20about%20the%20legal%20world%20order%E2%80%99%20he%20correctly%20pinpointed%20the%20main%20obstacle%20to%20the%20restoration%20of%20peace%3A%20the%20lack%20of%20agreement%20between%20the%20great%20powers%20on%20a%20legitimate%20world%20order.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ERussia%E2%80%99s%20claim%20that%20it%20had%20a%20right%20and%20indeed%20a%20duty%20to%20intervene%20in%20Ukraine%20to%20protect%20its%20integrity%20and%20security%20runs%20up%20against%20the%20doctrine%20that%20legally%20established%20frontiers%20must%20not%20be%20changed%20by%20force.%20However%2C%20existing%20frontiers%2C%20often%20the%20result%20of%20inventive%20colonial-era%20map-making%2C%20may%20not%20accord%20with%20current%20realities.%20How%2C%20then%2C%20to%20change%20frontiers%20peacefully%20if%20sentiment%20or%20security%20demand%20it%3F%20Clearly%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20idea%20of%20Ukraine%20as%20an%20integral%20part%20of%20itself%20was%20incompatible%20with%20Ukrainian%20nationalism.%20At%20the%20same%20time%2C%20Ukraine%E2%80%99s%20claim%2C%20backed%20by%20the%20West%2C%20to%20total%20sovereignty%20in%20foreign%20policy%2C%20is%20incompatible%20with%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20historical%20conception%20of%20its%20security%20needs.%20The%20disparity%20between%20these%20two%20mental%20fabrics%20is%20the%20biggest%20structural%20obstacle%20to%20peace.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3ESince%20the%20breakdown%20of%20the%20peace%20talks%20in%20April%202022%2C%20the%20military%20situation%20has%20scarcely%20changed%3A%20Russia%20is%20no%20nearer%20defeating%20a%20Ukraine%20supplied%20by%20NATO%2C%20and%20Ukraine%20is%20no%20nearer%20defeating%20its%20stronger%20neighbour.%20Time%20is%20on%20the%20side%20of%20Russia%20with%20its%20far%20greater%20resources%20of%20manpower%2C%20artillery%2C%20and%20airpower.%20In%20these%20circumstances%2C%20there%20will%20be%20a%20strong%20temptation%20on%20the%20Ukrainian%2FNATO%20side%20to%20break%20the%20stalemate%20by%20scaling%20up%20the%20warfare.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20danger%20of%20escalation%20should%20certainly%20not%20be%20discounted.%20Nor%20have%20economic%20sanctions%20decisively%20affected%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20ability%20to%20continue%20the%20war.%20The%20military%20stalemate%20prevents%20not%20just%20the%20resumption%20of%20%E2%80%98normality%E2%80%99%20within%20Ukraine%20and%20in%20Ukraine-Russian%20relations%20but%20stability%20in%20the%20world%20as%20a%20whole%2C%20unless%20we%20are%20willing%20to%20accept%20as%20%E2%80%98normal%E2%80%99%20the%20permanent%20division%20of%20the%20world%20into%20two%20antagonistic%20military%20and%20economic%20blocs.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EHistorians%20will%20naturally%20look%20to%20history%20for%20precedents%20and%20lessons.%20Ukraine%20has%20fought%20for%20its%20independence%20and%20won%2C%20much%20as%20Finland%20did%20in%201939-40.Admittedly%2C%20Finland%E2%80%99s%20independence%20came%20at%20the%20price%20of%20some%20territory.%20If%20we%20could%20think%20of%20the%20current%20Ukrainian%20achievement%20as%20a%20successful%20war%20of%20independence%2C%20we%20would%20be%20much%20less%20fixated%20on%20defining%20Ukrainian%20victory%20in%20terms%20of%20the%20reconquest%20of%20every%20bit%20of%20the%20map%20called%20Ukraine%20in%202014.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20idea%20of%20%E2%80%98security%20guarantees%E2%80%99%20for%20Ukraine%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3Eoutside%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Cspan%3E%20NATO%20in%20the%20Ukraine-Russian%20conversations%20of%20February-March%202022%20was%20groping%20towards%20the%20concept%20of%20a%20new%20security%20architecture%20to%20replace%20the%20NATO-Warsaw%20Pact%20system%20of%20the%20Cold%20War.%20Russia%20was%20demanding%20protection%20against%20NATO%3A%20Ukraine%20was%20seeking%20protection%20against%20Russia%20inside%20NATO.%20The%20compromise%20is%20a%20security%20structure%20of%20which%20NATO%20is%20a%20major%20but%20not%20the%20only%20part.%20Ukraine%E2%80%99s%20security%20should%20no%20more%20hinge%20on%20NATO%20membership%20than%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20on%20preventing%20Ukraine%E2%80%99s%20membership%20of%20NATO.%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EBill%20Burns%2C%20now%20director%20of%20the%20CIA%2C%20wrote%20in%201995%20that%20there%20was%20a%20need%20for%20a%20security%20order%20in%20Europe%20%E2%80%98sufficiently%20in%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20interests%20so%20that%20a%20revived%20Russia%20will%20have%20no%20compelling%20reason%20to%20revise%20it%E2%80%99.%20Instead%20NATO%20enlargement%2C%20he%20later%20wrote%2C%20had%20left%20%E2%80%9Ca%20mark%20on%20Russia%E2%80%99s%20relations%20with%20the%20West%20that%20would%20linger%20for%20decades%E2%80%9D.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20European%20(and%20indeed%20the%20global)%20security%20architecture%20should%20be%20one%20of%20%E2%80%98variable%20geometry%E2%80%99%2C%20with%20different%20structures%20of%20security%20provision%20available%20for%20different%20parts%20of%20the%20world%2C%20but%20with%20the%20whole%20tending%20to%20war%20prevention.%20A%20reformed%20Security%20Council%20of%20the%20United%20Nations%20should%20be%20the%20foundation%20(or%20arch)%20of%20any%20such%20design.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ENone%20of%20this%20will%20come%20to%20pass%20by%20thought%20alone.%20So%20we%20must%20rely%20on%20new%20(and%20possibly%20tragic)%20facts%20on%20the%20ground%20to%20provide%20the%20impetus%20to%20action.%20But%20when%20the%20facts%20allow%20it%2C%20thought%20should%20be%20ready%20to%20take%20advantage.%20That%20is%20why%20one%20should%20continuously%20talk%20up%20the%20need%20and%20advantages%20for%20peace%20today%2C%20even%20if%20its%20time%20is%20not%20yet.%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3ERobert%20Skidelsky%20is%20an%20economic%20historian%20and%20author%20of%20a%20three-volume%20award-winning%20biography%20of%20the%20economist%2C%20John%20Maynard%20Keynes.%20He%20is%20a%20member%20of%20the%20House%20of%20Lords.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1707572366000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F02%2F20165942%2F51905521463_0600c20141_k.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fworld%2Fwhy-peace-negotiations-between-russia-and-ukraine-failed%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22As%20the%20Ukrainian%20war%20approaches%20its%20second%20anniversary%2C%20there%20is%20renewed%2C%20if%20rather%20limp%2C%20talk%20of%20a%20ceasefire%20followed%20by%20negotiations.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A10%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fworld%2Fwhy-peace-negotiations-between-russia-and-ukraine-failed%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Vikrant%20requests%20paps%20not%20to%20click%20pics%20of%20his%20son%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1707572084000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fstatic.toiimg.com%2Fphoto%2Fmsid-107585976%2Cimgsize-67792.cms%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com%2Fentertainment%2Fhindi%2Fbollywood%2Fnews%2Fvikrant-massey-requests-paparazzi-not-to-click-photos-of-newborn-son-in-his-car-as-he-leave